article.headline: Mystics much improved for starters, at least
article.linkText: With hot rookie and Holdsclaw, Mystics open with victory
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- Stacey Dales-Schuman, the rookie who led
Oklahoma to the NCAA championship game this year, scored 23 points
as the Washington Mystics beat Orlando 93-82 on Saturday.

	   Chamique Holdsclaw, who missed two practices following the death
of her grandmother, added 19 points and 14 rebounds in the Mystics'
season opener.

	   ``The fact that she came back to practice at midweek and said
that she wanted to play just sent goose bumps down my back,''
first-year coach Marianne Stanley said. ``It really sent a message
to the rest of the team how badly she wants to win and just how
much responsibility she's ready to take.

	   ``What a statement of character -- I can't give her enough credit
for that.''

	   Helen Luz scored 13 of her career-high 15 points in the final 5 1/2
minutes for Washington, and second-year guard Coco Miller had
career highs of 13 points, four assists and four steals.

	   The Mystics never trailed, led by as many as 16 points, and
vaguely resembled last season's 10-22 team.

	   ``People have to understand right now that we have tremendous
versatility and we'll use it as we see fit,'' Staley said. ``Everybody on our team is comfortable in multiple roles and I'm
just so proud of them and happy for them.''

	   Shannon Johnson led the Miracle (1-1) with 22 points. Nykehsa
Sales scored 15 points, and Taj McWilliams-Franklin had 11 points
and seven rebounds.

	   ``They had a lot of energy,'' Sales said. ``They came out really
aggressive and we had no answer for them.''

	   Orlando coach Dee Brown said the answer is for the Miracle to
defend.
	   ``We gave up 93 points to a team that has trouble scoring,''
Brown said. ``We didn't play any defense. We didn't move our feet.

	   ``Marianne's a great coach. She ran an offense that was
tailor-made for our style of defense: Open the court up and run
back-doors while we were pressuring.''

	   Dales-Schuman also saluted her coach.

	   ``Ever since Marianne Stanley took over, we feel like a new team
this year,'' Dales-Schuman said. ``We're erasing all the past; we
don't have any issues; and we're ready to move on. I feel pretty
lucky to be here.

	   ``Our motto is to just play hard and enjoy ourselves.''

	   The game featured a WNBA-record 53 fouls, eclipsing the mark of
51 set by Utah and Sacramento on Aug. 19, 2001.

	   ``Hey, the majority of the fouls they called were fouls,'' Brown
said. ``We were not playing the defense that we can play, and that
was the most upsetting thing. Scoring points isn't a problem for
us.

	   ``That's the kind of game fans want to see, but I don't want to
see it from our end -- giving up 92 points. I like the game
exciting. I want to see it up and down. That was a good show for
the fans, but I don't want to be there, even though it does show
that women can play that style of game.''
